---
import Layout from "@layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "NoAI - A statement against generative AI";

const description =
  "A living document and writeup on the reasons I am opposed to the use of generative AI.";
---

<style lang="scss">
  h2 {
    border-top: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, currentColor 20%, transparent);
    padding-top: 1rem;
  }

  .unfinished {
    font-style: italic;
    opacity: 50%;
  }
</style>

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>{title}</h1>
  <p>
    I am strongly opposed to any form of AI being used, especially generative
    AI, be it text, image, video, or anything else. This page will serve as a
    living document and writeup of the reasons I am opposed to the use of
    generative AI.
  </p>

  <p>
    <b>Note:</b>
    This document is not finished. Any sections I have yet to start will be in italic
    and with darker text.
  </p>

  <section>
    <h2>Why?</h2>
    <p>
      For me there are more than a few reasons, but I'll separate them into four
      major categories of concern: The human factor, environmental, ethics and
      societal, and financial. While the human factor and ethics are closely
      related, they feel distinct enough for me to separate them into two
      separate categories.
    </p>
    <p>
      For simplicity's sake, whenever I refer to plain "AI", think Generative
      AI. Machine Learning (ML) is distinctively different, and not comparable
      to GenAI.
    </p>

    <section>
      <h3>The Human Factor</h3>
      <p>
        To me, the human factor is the most important argument against AI. It
        has the very noticeable impact of hampering your creative abilities, as
        well as affecting your critical thinking skills. It also creates a very
        false narrative that creating something is easy and requires no human
        input other than a prompt.
      </p>
      <p>
        Content generated by AI also has a <i>very</i> distinct lack of personality,
        and follows very set typing patterns.
      </p>
      <p>
        There is also the big issue of the "dead internet theory". Chatbots are
        being used more and more instead of people visiting sites organically.
        This means content that someone spends hours, days, weeks, or even
        longer on isn't actually being read at all. Further, a lot of pages
        block AI bots, making their content inaccessible to everyone using AI as
        their search engines.
      </p>

      <p class="unfinished">
        It seriously hampers your creative abilities. It seriously hinders and
        affects your critical thinking skills. It creates a false narrative that
        creating something is easy, automated and doesn't require human input
        other than a prompt.
      </p>
      <p class="unfinished">
        Organic website traffic, "dead internet theory", sites blocking
        chatbots, hallucinations. Reading algoslop instead of things someone
        spent hours on. Lack of human creativity and yank, aka loss of authetic
        human slop for example youtube poops
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Ethics and societal</h3>
      <p>
        On the more ethical problems, and problems affecting all of society
        there is the issue of bots changing how we write, and schools having to
        use their time and energy on "beating AI" instead of doing teaching and
        improving teaching materials.
      </p>
      <p>
        A good example of AI changing how we type is the em-dash. Before the era
        of chatbots, the em-dash was a sign of someone who knew how to type
        properly. Now, a lot of people are using it as an instant "aha!" when
        trying to detect AI content, even if said content was written completely
        organically by a human being.
      </p>

      <p class="unfinished">
        It's also doing long-term damage to education because it's forcing
        schools to use their time and energy on "beating AI" instead of actually
        teaching.
      </p>
      <p class="unfinished">
        one user vs whole society - "throwing trash in the nature" argument
      </p>
      <p class="unfinished">Trained on stolen content</p>
      <p class="unfinished">Emdash becoming a "forbidden character"</p>
      <p class="unfinished">
        the further destruction of the web as a human centred social community
      </p>
      <p class="unfinished">The erosion of trust in the visual medium</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Environmental</h3>
      <p class="unfinished">
        Water use, power use, temp changes? Increasing power prices in northern
        norway, nrk article
        https://www.nrk.no/nordland/open-ai-og-aker-bygger-datasenter-i-narvik.-det-kan-gjore-stromprisene-fem-ganger-sa-hoye-1.17516127
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Financial</h3>
      <p class="unfinished">
        Something something about the bubble, circular funding, hardware
        pricing, etc
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Other reasons</h3>
      <p class="unfinished">Code maintenance, spam AI PRs</p>
      <p class="unfinished">
        The erosion of documentation for coding is another factor that ive heard
        a bit
      </p>
      <p class="unfinished">
        about Hallucination of sources in research, high AI use -
        https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2502.00632
        https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.13812 https://arxiv.org/html/2601.18724v1
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Other commonly used reasons <i>for</i> AI</h2>
    <details>
      <summary>"I only use it as a search engine"</summary>
      <p>Improve your searching instead</p>
    </details>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>"But x, y, or z!"</h2>
    <p>
      This page isn't meant to list <i>every</i> type of AI or reasons against AI
      use. There are plenty of researchers trying to achieve good things through AI
      and Machine Learning, especially the medical field has some
      <i>really</i> fascinating use cases:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a
          href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10071847/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >
          Machine learning in medicine: what clinicians should know - PMC
        </a>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a
          href="https://ml-in-medicine.org/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >
          Machine Learning in Medicine - A Virtual Seminar Series
        </a>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a
          href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0010482522002505"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >
          Machine learning in medical applications: A review of state-of-the-art
          methods - ScienceDirect
        </a>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a
          href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2666990024000132"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >
          AI in diagnostic imaging: Revolutionising accuracy and efficiency -
          ScienceDirect
        </a>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Note that despite these possibly very good uses for Machine Learning, I am
      still critical of the use of GenAI in medicine, text and chat services
      especially. This is largely due to the potential for hallucinations and
      otherwise inncorrect or directly harmful information, as well as the
      massive privacy implications in regards to HIPAA, GDPR, and other privacy
      frameworks.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>

